ont-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">341</span></h2></td></tr><!--[if !supportMisalignedColumns]><tr style="height:0pt"><td style="width:213.15pt; border:none"></td><td style="width:213.15pt; border:none"></td></tr><![endif]--></table><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">COMPARING OFFSHORE SAFETY WITH OTHER COUNTRIES</span></h1><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Making a valid comparison between UK offshore operations and those of other countries is not straightforward because they have significant differences and because the statistical risk element can arise regardless of location.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Other offshore operation zon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es include North Sea operations from Norway, the Netherlands and Denmark, and operations in Africa (east and west coasts), Central and South America, the Middle East, Australasia, Asia and the Gulf of Mexico.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Factors to be taken into account when seeking</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to making valid comparisons include:</span></h2><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the numbers of oil and gas installations per zone and their distance from the shore and between each other;</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the number of passenger-carrying helicopters operating per zone;</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whether the helicopters are single or twin-en</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gined;</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the number of flight sectors/hours flown per year per zone; </span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the safety cultures present within the relevant companies and/or countries of operation;</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the operating environment (climate/weather conditions) per zone.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></h3><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Therefore, while it may seem int</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eresting to note that, in contrast with UK North Sea operations, there have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">been no serious incidents or accidents involving Norwegian or Danish operated Super Pumas in the North Sea </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">since the beginning of 2009, a direct comparison between those two zones </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of operations is not valid unless multiple factors of the type mentioned above are considered and taken into account (including the length of the sample period)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></h2><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">safety of offshore helicopter flights </span></h1><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Helicopters conduct operations that fixed wing aircraf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t cannot (for example, near the ground, without runways, and in harsh environments).  They provide a safe means of point to point transportation to and from offshore oil and gas installations.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The offshore environment can be very harsh because of regular</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> poor weather, often with reduced visibility, icing conditions, and the risk of lightning strikes.  Despite these challenges, offshore helicopter flights are actually safer, when compared on a per take-off basis, than is generally the case for fixed-wing c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommuter aircraft flights.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the context of the Committee's work, it is important to note that safety is dependent on multiple factors that, in turn, are under the control and/or influence of a wide range of different parties (including, but not limited to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, manufacturers, operators and maintenance organisations).  </span></h2><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 90pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Key factors include: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">  Relevant persons/organisations include:</span></h3><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:36pt; width:414pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:198pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The dependability of the helicopters used by the operators - this includes their suitability for the roles for which they are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">used</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; their design; continuing airworthiness support and management; and maintenance</span></h3></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:216pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">National/international regulators</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Helicopter designers/manufacturers</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Helicopter operators</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Maintenance providers</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Oil &amp; gas companies</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Training </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">organisations</span></h3></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:198pt"><h5 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dependability of the flight operations managed by the operators - this includes pilot working conditions; flight operational procedures; pilot performance; and maintenance</span></h5></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:216pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">National/international regulators </span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Helicopter designers/manufacturers</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Helicopter ope</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rators</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Pilots</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Continuing airworthiness management organisations </span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Maintenance providers</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Oil &amp; gas companies</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Training </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">organisations</span></h3></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:198pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The dependability of helicopter landing and take-off sites, and air navigation and air traffic management services</span></h3></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:216pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">National/international regulators</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Heliport/helideck designers and managers</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Air navigation service providers</span></h3></td></tr><tr><td style="border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:198pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Climate/weather conditions and the operating environment generally</span></h3></td><td style="border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:216pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></h3></td></tr></table><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></h3><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Should an accident occur, various other factors become relevant to its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">immediate safety consequences.  These largely relate to the parties identified above (but also include persons involved in air and sea search and rescue operations (SARS).  Some examples of consequential safety factors that can be influenced by such partie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s include:</span></h2><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 126pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-90pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">impact absorption capabilities of helicopters and seats upon a hard landing;</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 126pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-90pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">floatation/stability of helicopters on the sea surface;</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cabin safety for pilots and passengers;</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">survival equipment for pilots and passengers;</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">emergency locator equipmen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t;</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 126pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-90pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">preparedness of pilots and passengers to deal with emergencies; and</span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">emergency preparedness of heliport/helideck operators and SARS.</span></h3><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Eurocopter designed and built range of Super Puma helicopters has been one of the principal work horses of the North Sea for over 30 years.  Three models in that range are currently used by UK operators: the AS332L1 (the Mk I Super Puma); the AS332L2 (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Mk II Super Puma), and the EC225LP model.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Mk II differs from the earlier Mk I in that it is fitted with an electronic flight instrumentation system, redesigned rotor heads, and up-rated engines and transmission.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Mk II and the EC225 are the only offshore helicopters where, in the event of failure of one of its two engines, integration of the engine management, vehicle and autopilot systems ensures that the correct power, speed and flight path are automatically </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">maintained.  This reduces crew workload and provides maximum safety.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Development of the Mk II led to the EC225, which incorporates a five-bladed rotor head and increased engine power.  It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is also fitted with Automatic Altitude Protection, providing in-bu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ilt clearance from terrain and other traffic, whilst ensuring the safe management of the flight path during normal operations, engine failures and degraded flight crew performance.  It is also the only helicopter with an emergency lubrication system for it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s main gearbox.  The EC225 is one of the most advanced helicopters in the world.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A wide range of equipment is fitted as standard to Super Pumas used offshore; examples include: emergency floats; helicopter emergency egress lighting; liferafts; automatic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">deployable emergency locator transmitter; helicopter enhanced ground proximity warning systems; underwater locator beacon; automatic voice alarm device; search and weather radar; radar altimeter with audio warning; ARMS™/HUMS™; cockpit door jettison; trafﬁ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c collision and avoidance system; push-out windows; public address system; emergency lighting; and high energy absorption landing gear.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All in all, the Super Puma well embodies the safety philosophy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of Eurocopter by its use of many developments and technol</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ogies.  This is widely </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  For example</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the high energy absorption landing gear fitted to the EC225 has been praised by pilots worldwide and become the new standard of excellence.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he majority of all civilian Super Pumas (approx. 70% in the case</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the Mk II version) are flown by offshore operators.  They</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are well suited to the offshore role.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Worldwide (in 2013), the Super Puma family (including military versions) accumulated over 4.8 million flying hours of service, including over 3.8 million h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ours in the case of the Mk I, 0.7 million hours in the case of the Mk II, and over 0.3 million hours in the case of the newer EC225.  All three models have built up a strong safety record.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">No aircraft type or manufacturer is immune to the occurrence of ser</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ious incidents and accidents.  In every such case </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a thorough, impartial and objective analysis of all the available evidence is undertaken with a view to building a picture of all the reasons underlying causation and therefore identifying the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">action and/or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> omission and/or condition and/or circumstance which if eliminated or avoided would have prevented the occurrence of the accident or mitigated the resulting injuries or damage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.    </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Since the beginning of 2009, offshore operated UK registered Super Pumas h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ave been involved in five separate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">offshore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> accidents, two of which had tragic consequences (one in April 2009 and the second in August 2013).</span></h2><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:36pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:193.5pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">February 2009 </span></h3></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:220.5pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">involved an EC225 which, during a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">night visual approach to an oil platform, descended in controlle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d flight onto the surface of the sea, following which it remained upright supported by its floatation equipment which had inflated automatically: all those on board were able to evacuate the helicopter safely before being successfully rescued.  </span></h3></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:193.5pt"><h5 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">April 2009 </span></h5></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:220.5pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">involved a Mk II, but is the subject of a Fatal Accident Inquiry in Scotland starting on 6 January 2014.</span></h3></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:193.5pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">May and October 2012 </span></h3></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:220.5pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">involved EC225s which, by reason of mechanical failures, each had to undertake a controlled landing on the surface of the sea.  In both cases, the helicopter's </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">floatation equipment inflated to support the helicopter on the sea surface and all those on boar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d were able to safely evacuate into the helicopter's liferafts before being successfully rescued.  These two accidents remain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">under investigation by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Air Accidents Branch of the Department for Transport (AAIB).</span></h3></td></tr><tr><td style="border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:193.5pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">August 2013 </span></h3></td><td style="border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:220.5pt"><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">involved a Mk II and remains </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">under investigation by the AAIB, though an interim AAIB Bulletin stated "</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">To date, the wreckage examination and analysis of the recorded data have not found any evidence of a technical fault that could have been causal to the ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">cident, although some work remains to be completed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">"</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></h3></td></tr></table><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter products and services involve many disciplines, for example: design, development flight tests, production, continuing airworthiness, training, maintenance, and quality assurance.  Ensuring the safety of the helicopter is an overarching priority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of all disciplines.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Exacting national and international safety certification standards apply to every Eurocopter helicopter.  No Eurocopter helicopter is permitted to fly unless it meets such standards.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whenever a Eurocopter helicopter is supplied to th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e UK offshore sector, it also meets additional requirements specific to such operations including, for example, the mandatory fitting of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">HUMS™ (an acronym for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Health and Usage Monitoring System</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">HUMS™</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was developed to capture flight data for analysis on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the ground, to monitor an aircraft's performance, and to assist in spotting and troubleshooting anomalies early.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensors (located on various areas of the dynamic components of the helicopter), software and ground tools are used mainly to monitor vibratio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n levels and thereafter to analyse vibration data.  The purpose of the condition indicators is to calculate frequencies that highlight known failures and, therefore, to provide a constant check on the presence of possible anomalies.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter provides i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ts customers with complete and accurate information regarding its helicopters to ensure airworthiness upon delivery and during subsequent operation and maintenance.  In addition to providing manuals of the type listed below in support of the safe operation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and maintenance of helicopters after delivery (in the most cost-effective manner possible) type-rating training is also provided to each operator's pilots upon delivery using specialist Eurocopter simulators, and training is provided to aircraft technicia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ns using advanced educational tools.</span></h2><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Flight operations: the Flight Manual (FM) for pilots provides information such as operating procedures, limitations, performance data and other technical information. </span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Maintenance: technical publications contain units o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f data for maintenance and repair, description and identification of parts and the helicopter itself including airborne and ground equipment.  </span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Procurement and identification manuals (parts and tools catalogues): these provide lists and illustrations that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">allow for the identification of parts and tools required for spares or repairs as well as their procurement.  </span></h3><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This documentation covers standard and customized aircraft installations as well as optional equipment and is provided in one or more of the foll</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">owing formats: paper, PDFs, web-based Interactive Electronic Technical Publication (IETP) including advanced functions such as hyperlinks, search engines, possibility to customize documentation and to order spares from the catalogue, periodic updates, etc.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">4.18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter provides operators and maintenance organisations with ongoing support including, for example, training, technical support, HUMS support, and immediate access to information about helicopters for which they are responsible and how to keep them </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">operational: Eurocopter has a designated Technical Information Publication on the Internet (T.I.P.I.) website that issues publications in real time.</span></h2><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">improving safety of offshore flights by the industry</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter has comprehensive safety management process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es for improving safety, identifying and dealing with hazards that are inimical to safety, and eliminating the possibility of safety occurrences.  Each Eurocopter helicopter type is subject to a Continued Airworthiness programme which collects, investigate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s and analyses reports and data on failures, malfunctions or other events which could adversely affect the continued airworthiness of the product, component or equipment denoted in a type certificate.  As part of that programme, EASA is kept closely inform</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed of any instance where an event or circumstance may impact adversely on safety.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the context of a continued airworthiness programme, Eurocopter may upgrade the original design, to either (i) remedy an issue that may compromise a product's airworthine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ss condition or produce an unsafe situation or (ii) obtain higher efficiency.  These upgrades, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">preventive and/or corrective actions are notified to Eurocopter's customers through Service Bulletins (SB), Alert Service Bulletins (ASB), or Emergency Alert Ser</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vice Bulletins (EASB), according to their discretionary or mandatory nature.  Technical and operational publications that are developed and issued by Eurocopter are available to operators through a dedicated web based tool.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As discussed earlier, the accident/incident investigation process represents an important tool in the development of countermeasures to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">contribute to the continuous improvement of safety</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Root causes are often multiple and regularly relate to matters outside Eurocopter's control such as operational conditions, pilot behavior, and maintenance acts.  Countermeasures can focus on matters such as maintenance, training of flight crews, the organ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">isation of flight, as well as improvement of the helicopter design (e.g. through design and certification of new parts).  Where necessary, such measures are devised and implemented before the relevant results of an official accident investigation are relea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sed.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition to reacting to circumstances and events in the way outlined in the preceding paragraphs, Eurocopter is regularly engaged in initiatives which have proactive safety benefits; for example:</span></h2><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter is actively supporting the three main U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">K North Sea operators in their recently announced joint review of safety-related practices, procedures, training and equipment.  </span></h3><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In relation to helicopters with glass cockpits and use of hands-off flying, Eurocopter is supporting operators by actively wor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">king on the creation and maintenance in operational conditions of a Flight Crew Operating Manual (FCOM) of the type widely used already by Boeing and Airbus in relation to large transport jets: this will reduce the scope for pilot error.</span></h3><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s and proposes to operators (on a continuous basis) safety improvements in relation the Eurocopter helicopters they use (for example, providing equipment improving situation awareness for pilots).  </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter is engaged in regular research (innovative saf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ety-related programmes) in relation to the development of new models of helicopters for the future. </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter deploys (on a regular basis) new training means and training syllabuses for flight crew and maintenance personnel (for example, the recent intro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">duction of an EC225 full flight simulator in Aberdeen for pilot training).</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter continues to be actively involved in an on-going initiative of the International Helicopter Safety Team ((IHST) a team of industry leaders and governments (including the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK)) regarding factors influencing the international civil helicopter accident rate and procedures that could be established to reduce it.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Since the outset of that initiative in 2006, Eurocopter has prioritised the importance of, and devoted considerable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resources to, different working groups in different regions of the world (especially in the USA and Europe).  Eurocopter's contributions cover matters such as IHST safety promotion materials (e.g. safety management system toolkit, training toolkit, mainten</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ance toolkit, DIVE video, decision making leaflet, risk management in training leaflet).  Eurocopter's Head of Fleet Safety is currently a director at the IHST EXCOM and co-chair of the EHEST, the European Branch of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">IHST and actively engages to further</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> work relating to safety standards across the industry.</span></h2><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:none">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">conclusion</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter believes that it is important to have a strong regulatory system in relation to all aspects of helicopter operations.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:none">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eurocopter would welcome any opportunity to contribute to an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y future dialogue regarding further interaction between regulators and the wider industry on the issue of whether there is a role and benefit for additional regulation or standard setting across the UK offshore flight operation.</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></h2><div style="border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.75pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-top:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="bkmCurrentVersion"></a></p></div></div></body></html>